    base:desc "The lifecycle of the Digital Twin is anchored in a Model‑Based Systems‑Engineering (MBSE) development phase that is split into four abstraction levels often referred to as RFLP: (1) Requirements modeling, (2) Functional‑architecture modeling, (3) Logical‑architecture modeling, and (4) Product/technical‑layer modeling. At each level a concrete representation is created with SysML artifacts (requirement diagrams, block definition diagrams, internal block diagrams, parametric diagrams). After the abstract models are defined, a Digital‑Shadow Reference Model (a UML class diagram) is instantiated; this concretization step maps reference concepts to concrete classes and relations, producing a concrete digital shadow. The digital shadow then serves as the basis for the full Digital Twin by adding active processing components, simulation or data‑calculation models, and traceability links (the ‘originates‑from’ association) that connect generated data traces back to their originating processing component and input traces. Transition between stages is governed by the conformance relation defined in the reference model, ensuring that each concrete realization satisfies the structural and semantic constraints of the abstract model."
]

